**Roadmap Announcement: **

As you probably already saw based on Szymon’s post, we are planning a refactor of the IOTA codebase. These first few weeks have given us a couple of insights; namely:
- This whole thing actually can work
- Miners are crazy good at optimizing code and our poor orchestrator can’t keep up
- Our validation is very promising, but will still need to be improved

In order to resolve most of our current issues, we will need a horizontally scalable orchestrator. We knew this was unavoidable as we plan on having much more miners in the long run, but it’s showing to be necessary earlier than expect.

1) Horizontal scaling - we will refactor the architecture of the subnet to use a database with multiple copies of orchestrator instances to reduce strain on the Orchestrator. Some API endpoints will change in the process.
2) Miner and Validator code will be updated to be compatible with the architecture change 
3) Core refactor to take place next week with a further week for testing and bug fixing; re-launch EXPECTED WEEK COMMENCING 21 JULY 
4) Miner emissions return to 80% burn while we implement these changes - this may be incrementally reduced as we approach launch, depending on our progress. We plan to create a variable burn which is based on subnet performance to encourage self-regulation of the subnet. i.e: If you DDoS the orchestrator and it dies, emissions go down, if everyone contributes nicely, emissions go up.


With these changes implemented and successful continuous training runs enabled, we will progress with improved validation mechanism work over the summer. We expect to see a refined, successful 15B training run through the summer months and plan to scale up to a significantly larger model size some time in the autumn.

## Some updates regarding the system redesign 💻 

1. We have refactored the entire codebase into a monorepo, separating the dependancies for miners, validators, and the orchestrator to allow us to scale
2. We are using NeonDB to store the state of the activation store, weights store, and all other information in order to make the orchestrator stateless. (looks like image 1) 
3. We are in tandem also analyzing the staibility of the network and the proportion of backwards/forwards passes that get through all the layers of the network (image 2/3). The results are leading to a roughly 17.5% throughput which is very low for the amount of work we are doing. We need to improve this and it's one of the top debugging priorities. I believe it's coming from reverted states and this only gets worse when miners are unresponsive (ie: you're still registered on the network and miner is operational but you're not actually running the GPU, which is what it looks like, image 4).

## Continuing ▶️ 
The team is working towards getting the system operational on testnet this week. We are all meeting in person next week to continue working on the design. There are many edge cases that occur when you're attempting to cast a stateful system into a stateless design, as there are async loops / counters that you rely on the ensure states are moving as expected. You can think of it as an AC/DC clock. This is stateful and needs to be separated out from the orchestrator, so these things take a bit longer to test

## Burn 🔥 
Burn will stay on for the remaining days. Depending on the results we have, we may turn down burn from 100% --> 80% next week but I cannot make a promise about this. I hope your GPUs are warm doing other things 🙂

Hey guys, I'm sure you missed seeing training loss curves :notstonks: on our dashboard, so I'm sharing some of the research results we've been up to recently.

As you know, we've been working on activation and activation-gradient compression for the past few months. This is critical for enabling pipeline parallelism on IOTA. In the technical primer we published back in May (https://www.macrocosmos.ai/research/iota_primer.pdf), we communicated some early results of a compression method we designed. We managed to obtain a 128x compression rate on a 3-bottleneck 1.5B llama-based architecture.

The results we showed in the report were obtained by training on 50M tokens of FineWeb, which is a quite small set. In LLM pre-training literature, it is common to report preliminary results on tens or even hundreds of billions of tokens, so we promised to scale up our training and show more results to confirm whether our compression method would still maintain the same performance relative to the baseline with no compression. I am basically fulfilling this promise in this post:6179zuckerbergcoffee: 

You can see in the plot I attached two training runs of a 1.5B model: one with 3 bottlenecks and one without (baseline). Both on ~40B FineWeb tokens. You can see that the bottleneck model still keeps a decent performance relative to the baseline, which is GREAT NEWS 🚀   It seems that the early positive signs we reported in the primer were maintained when scaling up, but still quite early to retire :cattocry:  we will need to push  further along this path.

This scaled-up run highlighted a few issues that we are working on:

1. The baseline performance itself is still lower than a 1.5B LLaMA SOTA model trained on a comparable number of tokens. This could be due to untuned hyperparameters or to our reduced sequence length of 800 (4096 is commonly used in SOTA). We need a few more scale-up runs to tune that baseline.

2. There is still a small gap between the 3-bottleneck model and the baseline. We are currently investigating if this gap can be filled with better hyperparameter tuning. We are also aiming at testing both models on SOTA benchmarks to assess the impact of this small loss gap.

3. We need to push the number of bottlenecks to the extreme and assess the impact on loss with respect to the baseline. We have already started some experiments in that direction, with some encouraging results that we will communicate in the near future. Adding a bottleneck after every transform block is what we need to make IOTA run on your MacBooks 😉

We will maintain a comparable number of bottlenecks and a 128x compression rate on IOTA in the immediate future based on this results. While we carry  on our research in parallel to improve compression an lower infra requirement on the miners' side. I'll be posting regular updates.

Many thanks to @roel [τ, α] | Macrocosmos who helped  getting these experiments out. Let me know if you have any questions. I'll also be tomorrow on Inventive Mechanisms to answer any questions.

Yup, adding to this we finally have loss consistently going down - there were 3 main issues:
- dtype issues during upload: We had one particularly sneaky bug where casting from torch to numpy changed the dtype such that on loading weights back in we got nonsense values. When applying the optimizer steps (later down the line) this proceeded to then cause NaNs.
- Miscounting of activations: During merging, weights are weighted based on how many activaitons each miner trained on. Unfortunately due to how deletions were cascading in the database, one layer finishing the merge led to a miscount of activations for the remaining layers, messing up convergence.
- Model reloading: We reload the model each epoch before filling it with the available weights. When miners failed to upload weights, the reloading caused the optimizer state to reset (instead of staying at the old values), therefore making the convergence fail as well.

1. Initially, we run *local* tests, where we run N number of miners (with > 2 miners per layer), with something that we can manage on a single machine with multiple versions of the model (100M). We can move much faster this way, testing our development dashboards, looking at run statistics, testing the local dbs. 

2. Once things look good here, we go to our Kubernetes deployment layer, which spins up 3 orchestrators, a scheduler instance, and all the miners. Each miner with its own machine, an A100. This allows us to test larger models like a 1B or 15B, without any potential for shared memory on a single-node system. We monitor the system using the development dashboards, as well as a staging dashboard of the *real* IOTA dashboard (iota.macrocosmos.ai)

3. Since we are in the production setup at this point, we use tools like prometheus and grafana to look at system-level metrics, and we use a platform called OpenSearch (https://opensearch.org/) to look at *all* the logs across *all* of our machines. IE: If we are running (3 orch, 1 scheduler, 20 miners, we can look at the logs for 24 DIFFERENT machines at the same time, filter across them, ect..)
